The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	Srinagar, Feb. 12: A senior BSF officer has landed in trouble after his subordinates named him for allegedly ordering the shooting of Zahid Farooq, a 16-year-old boy, last week.          
	The officer, who was leading a convoy of 12 personnel, had ordered constable Lakhwinder Kumar, arrested for killing Zahid, to fire at him, police investigation is said to have revealed.                  
	New Delhi: US national Winston Marshall Charmichael, who was detained at Indira Gandhi International Airport on Wednesday after a knife was found in his baggage, does not seem to have any links to any terror organisation, priliminary investigations have revealed.                  
	Chandigarh (PTI): The youth who had attacked with a pocket knife former police officer S.P.S. Rathore, who has been convicted of molesting Ruchika Girhotra, was granted bail on Friday. Utsav Sharma, 29, who is said to be suffering from a psychological disorder, had stabbed Rathore thrice in the cheek on Monday.                  
	Mumbai (PTI): Bombay High Court has ruled that a teachers sexual exploitation of a student on the promise of helping her pass an exam amounts to rape. The court upheld the five-year imprisonment handed to Sanjay Gondchar, convicted of raping a Class IX girl.                   
	Melbourne (PTI): Two Indian brothers were murdered, allegedly by an Indian student, after a dispute over money in Perth on Friday. The accused has been arrested.                  
	New Delhi (PTI): The Supreme Court has ruled that desertion cannot be an excuse to apply for divorce if a husband or wife is compelled to live separately because of constant torture or harassment by the other.                  
	New Delhi, (PTI): The PMO has asked all ministries to take its approval before using the Prime Ministers photographs.                                                                                                                                              
